WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.210 --> 00:00:03.980
Prof: Let me start.
 

00:00:03.980 --> 00:00:08.010
I'm going to read you something
and you have to guess what kind

00:00:08.010 --> 00:00:09.830
of a scene I'm describing.
 

00:00:09.830 --> 00:00:13.856
"A ghostly stillness
descended over the country,

00:00:13.856 --> 00:00:17.030
this country today,
with every restaurant,

00:00:17.030 --> 00:00:20.360
bar and teahouse in the country
closed.

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:25.281
Every store shuttered and
police patrolling the streets to

00:00:25.281 --> 00:00:29.080
make sure no citizen dare to
step outside.

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:32.491
Avenues normally clogged with
traffic were so empty that

00:00:32.491 --> 00:00:36.275
picnics could have been held on
them, except that nobody would

00:00:36.275 --> 00:00:38.260
have been allowed to attend.
 

00:00:38.260 --> 00:00:42.122
Plazas that are perpetual
nightmares of congestion and

00:00:42.122 --> 00:00:46.350
exhaust fumes were abandoned to
wandering dogs and cats.

00:00:46.350 --> 00:00:50.770
It was also a good day for the
fish because the thousands of

00:00:50.770 --> 00:00:54.815
fishermen who line the
shorelines on Sunday were all at

00:00:54.815 --> 00:00:55.490
home.
 

00:00:55.490 --> 00:00:58.987
The waterway itself,
one of the world's busiest

00:00:58.987 --> 00:01:03.170
waterways, was as flat and
silent as a woodland pond.

00:01:03.170 --> 00:01:07.182
The government decreed a
six-month term--jail term for

00:01:07.182 --> 00:01:10.739
any citizen who didn't spend the
day at home.

00:01:10.739 --> 00:01:14.456
All in all, the country today
looked like a land on which a

00:01:14.456 --> 00:01:18.367
neutron bomb had been dropped
devastating the population while

00:01:18.367 --> 00:01:21.060
leaving the buildings
undamaged."

00:01:21.060 --> 00:01:23.019
What do you think it is?
 

00:01:23.019 --> 00:01:25.069
It's drastic.
 

00:01:25.069 --> 00:01:26.799
Student:  The plague?
 

00:01:26.799 --> 00:01:30.030
Prof: Nope,
good, reasonable guess,

00:01:30.030 --> 00:01:30.739
but no.
 

00:01:30.739 --> 00:01:34.709
Governments weren't as strong
then.

00:01:34.709 --> 00:01:38.709
It's the census day in Turkey.
 

00:01:38.709 --> 00:01:42.873
Some places take their census'
very seriously and require that

00:01:42.873 --> 00:01:47.242
people really be in the place of
their residence so that they can

00:01:47.242 --> 00:01:51.340
be counted and that they get a
very good set of numbers.

00:01:51.340 --> 00:01:57.887
The waterway that they're
talking about between Europe and

00:01:57.887 --> 00:02:00.530
Asia running through?
 

00:02:00.530 --> 00:02:01.349
Student:  The Bosporus.
 

00:02:01.349 --> 00:02:02.890
Prof: The Bosporus,
right.

00:02:02.890 --> 00:02:05.688
Now compare this to another
country.

00:02:05.688 --> 00:02:10.859
An educated and motivated guy
got one of the temporary jobs as

00:02:10.859 --> 00:02:12.300
a census taker.
 

00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:16.388
He was high class enough to get
an article published in The

00:02:16.388 --> 00:02:17.930
Atlantic Monthly.
 

00:02:17.930 --> 00:02:19.377
This is New York City.
 

00:02:19.377 --> 00:02:21.750
I'll tell you because you'll
guess.

00:02:21.750 --> 00:02:24.039
He was 6'4" and Caucasian.
 

00:02:24.039 --> 00:02:26.520
They sent him to Chinatown.
 

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:30.680
People took one look at him and
slammed the door.

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:33.780
Others offered him money to go
away;

00:02:33.780 --> 00:02:38.291
even most of those who tried to
cooperate did not have time to

00:02:38.291 --> 00:02:40.139
fill out the long form.
 

00:02:40.139 --> 00:02:42.930
He asked to be assigned to
another area.

00:02:42.930 --> 00:02:45.318
He got Wall Street.
 

00:02:45.318 --> 00:02:47.930
Same story, no one would
cooperate with him.

00:02:47.930 --> 00:02:51.997
He couldn't even get into one
building, but this was a

00:02:51.997 --> 00:02:54.300
motivated guy,
like a Yalie.

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:56.818
He climbed onto the roof of the
next building,

00:02:56.818 --> 00:02:59.628
the building next door,
he jumped over the partition,

00:02:59.628 --> 00:03:03.360
not across the street but over
the partition --

00:03:03.360 --> 00:03:08.490
to get into the building that
he was supposed to take the

00:03:08.490 --> 00:03:09.590
census of.
 

00:03:09.590 --> 00:03:12.830
Right there on the roof was a
dilapidated shack.

00:03:12.830 --> 00:03:15.080
Okay maybe someone's living in
the shack.

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:19.804
He knocks on the door,
someone inside flings open the

00:03:19.804 --> 00:03:20.438
door.
 

00:03:20.438 --> 00:03:25.084
Inside he could see several
apparently naked people lying on

00:03:25.084 --> 00:03:26.580
hospital gurneys.
 

00:03:26.580 --> 00:03:30.324
The man who opened the door was
wearing a white coat,

00:03:30.324 --> 00:03:31.764
"Go away!"
 

00:03:31.764 --> 00:03:34.502
He screamed,
"I'm giving my wife a

00:03:34.502 --> 00:03:36.158
cancer treatment."
 

00:03:36.158 --> 00:03:37.598
New York City.
 

00:03:37.598 --> 00:03:42.116
A more experienced census taker
told him that he wasn't doing it

00:03:42.116 --> 00:03:42.690
right.
 

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:45.413
What you have to do is what
they say, "curbstone

00:03:45.413 --> 00:03:45.990
it".
 

00:03:45.990 --> 00:03:49.893
What that means is you sit on
the sidewalk and guess how many

00:03:49.893 --> 00:03:52.038
apartments are in the building.
 

00:03:52.038 --> 00:03:54.266
You look up at the building,
you guess how many apartments

00:03:54.266 --> 00:03:56.931
in the building,
and fill out that many forms

00:03:56.931 --> 00:04:00.979
with guesses about how many
people live in each apartment.

00:04:00.979 --> 00:04:04.098
That's the way censuses are
done in New York City,

00:04:04.098 --> 00:04:05.688
a comparison to Turkey.
 

00:04:05.688 --> 00:04:10.310
Now these are describing the
1990 Census.

00:04:10.310 --> 00:04:13.468
I'll get to the 2000 Census in
a moment.

00:04:13.468 --> 00:04:16.639
That census was the most
expensive ever,

00:04:16.639 --> 00:04:19.079
it missed more than two million
children,

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:21.819
of course mostly minority
children,

00:04:21.819 --> 00:04:24.600
and imagine what this does for
school planning,

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:27.730
etcetera, etcetera,
it missed all together--

00:04:27.730 --> 00:04:31.480
not counting just children--ten
million people and it double

00:04:31.480 --> 00:04:34.649
counted,
or it counted in the wrong

00:04:34.649 --> 00:04:37.879
place another six million
people.

00:04:37.879 --> 00:04:41.882
Between censuses the census
bureau uses the count of the

00:04:41.882 --> 00:04:44.649
last census to make its
projections.

00:04:44.649 --> 00:04:47.440
They know the population is
increasing every year,

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:49.490
how much do we have now,
now, now?

00:04:49.490 --> 00:04:52.942
By the time they came from the
1990 to the 2000 Census,

00:04:52.942 --> 00:04:56.458
there were seven million more
people in America then the

00:04:56.458 --> 00:04:58.759
Census Bureau thought there was.
 

00:04:58.759 --> 00:05:02.744
The population had been
increasing something like one

00:05:02.744 --> 00:05:06.269
and half times what they had
thought it was.

00:05:06.269 --> 00:05:07.810
Does this slop matter?
 

00:05:07.810 --> 00:05:11.129
The poor quality of the United
States census.

00:05:11.129 --> 00:05:15.303
Well, nowadays these numbers
might seem small but more than

00:05:15.303 --> 00:05:19.262
$185 billion dollars a year in
federal aid to states are

00:05:19.262 --> 00:05:22.790
apportioned according to the
census results,

00:05:22.790 --> 00:05:25.889
so every state really wants its
people counted.

00:05:25.889 --> 00:05:28.062
On top of that,
what else is apportioned

00:05:28.062 --> 00:05:29.509
depending on the census?
 

00:05:29.509 --> 00:05:33.081
Congress, the House of
Representatives is apportioned,

00:05:33.081 --> 00:05:37.124
so people want their state to
have as many representatives as

00:05:37.124 --> 00:05:38.000
possible.
 

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.509
Given the importance of this,
why is it so bad?

00:05:41.509 --> 00:05:45.430
Why is the U.S.***Census so bad?
 

00:05:45.430 --> 00:05:48.269
The answer is primarily
politics.

00:05:48.269 --> 00:05:51.185
It is well known,
the kind of problems that this

00:05:51.185 --> 00:05:54.350
census taker had in New York is
very well known,

00:05:54.350 --> 00:05:57.848
and it's well known that these
people that are considered

00:05:57.848 --> 00:05:59.910
somewhat marginal:
minorities,

00:05:59.910 --> 00:06:03.709
immigrants, poor people,
they are heavily undercounted.

00:06:03.709 --> 00:06:05.389
This is well known.
 

00:06:05.389 --> 00:06:09.117
The problem is that these
people don't vote Republican and

00:06:09.117 --> 00:06:12.519
when this story that I'm telling
you takes place,

00:06:12.519 --> 00:06:15.439
the Republicans controlled the
House of Representatives,

00:06:15.439 --> 00:06:20.980
which controls the budget.
 

00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:25.720
The census has been missing
this eight--

00:06:25.720 --> 00:06:28.468
ten million for the 1990
Census, eight million for

00:06:28.468 --> 00:06:30.384
before,
roughly eight to ten million

00:06:30.384 --> 00:06:33.189
people,
and again, it's these minority

00:06:33.189 --> 00:06:35.002
groups,
minorities, renters,

00:06:35.002 --> 00:06:37.365
urban dwellers,
and so Democrats--and they

00:06:37.365 --> 00:06:40.887
generally vote Democrat--
and the Democrats have been

00:06:40.887 --> 00:06:46.100
pushing to get them counted,
to make an accurate account.

00:06:46.100 --> 00:06:50.254
But a Republican redistricting
expert wrote a memorandum in

00:06:50.254 --> 00:06:54.697
1997 predicting that adjustment
could cost the Republican Party

00:06:54.697 --> 00:06:58.290
24 house seats,
which is a huge amount.

00:06:58.290 --> 00:07:00.641
So, since then,
the Republicans have blocked

00:07:00.641 --> 00:07:02.500
any modernization of the census.
 

00:07:02.500 --> 00:07:07.132
For the year 2000 Census,
President Clinton appointed a

00:07:07.132 --> 00:07:11.764
new director of the Census
Bureau, a woman named Martha

00:07:11.764 --> 00:07:14.939
Riche who we've had here at
Yale.

00:07:14.939 --> 00:07:18.574
She came out of a scientific
and research environment and was

00:07:18.574 --> 00:07:21.846
really very competent,
scholarly, knew how to do it

00:07:21.846 --> 00:07:24.182
right,
and she announced when she came

00:07:24.182 --> 00:07:26.327
into office,
"All industrial

00:07:26.327 --> 00:07:29.949
democracies will be holding a
census in the year 2000.

00:07:29.949 --> 00:07:33.834
We want the United States to
win a gold medal for

00:07:33.834 --> 00:07:35.209
accuracy."
 

00:07:35.209 --> 00:07:36.259
She thought she was smart.
 

00:07:36.259 --> 00:07:39.637
In fact of course she missed
the boat, because she thought

00:07:39.637 --> 00:07:42.185
she was supposed to make an
accurate census,

00:07:42.185 --> 00:07:44.970
and no, that wasn't what she
was hired for.

00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:50.206
What she had proposed was a
statistical way of dealing with

00:07:50.206 --> 00:07:50.839
this.
 

00:07:50.839 --> 00:07:53.610
You know the groups that you've
missed,

00:07:53.610 --> 00:07:55.730
you know where they live,
so after you've counted

00:07:55.730 --> 00:07:58.029
everyone as well as you can in
the whole country,

00:07:58.029 --> 00:07:59.860
you go back to the inner city
neighborhoods,

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:03.807
the various places where you
know that you're going to miss

00:08:03.807 --> 00:08:06.870
people and you really blanket
that and do--

00:08:06.870 --> 00:08:09.420
those areas very carefully,
a sample across the country.

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:12.309
Then you find out what your
errors are in that large sample

00:08:12.309 --> 00:08:14.699
and then you can adjust the
whole population,

00:08:14.699 --> 00:08:17.610
assuming you made the same
mistakes everywhere.

00:08:17.610 --> 00:08:22.740
She was very open,
that's what she planned to do.

00:08:22.740 --> 00:08:25.860
At the time,
though, Newt Gingrich,

00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:29.396
I don't know if you know that
name with the New Deal for

00:08:29.396 --> 00:08:32.837
America or something,
was the Speaker of the House,

00:08:32.837 --> 00:08:35.423
controlled the budget,
and he said,

00:08:35.423 --> 00:08:38.970
'yup, you have the authority to
do that,

00:08:38.970 --> 00:08:40.668
you're the Director of the
budget ,

00:08:40.668 --> 00:08:44.005
but, if you do that,
I will cut your budget to

00:08:44.005 --> 00:08:44.600
zero.'
 

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:49.071
Basically she wasn't allowed to
do that and so she had to

00:08:49.071 --> 00:08:49.788
resign.
 

00:08:49.788 --> 00:08:55.024
She just would not do a census
that was less then what we're

00:08:55.024 --> 00:08:56.710
capable of doing.
 

00:08:56.710 --> 00:09:00.339
The census was done the old
fashioned way,

00:09:00.339 --> 00:09:05.294
it cost $1.7 billion dollars
more than it would have with

00:09:05.294 --> 00:09:09.808
sampling and was not anywhere
near as accurate.

00:09:09.808 --> 00:09:14.720
Now these same considerations
apply almost everywhere.

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:18.231
In China, for instance,
you know about the one child

00:09:18.231 --> 00:09:22.020
policy and the government is
strongly trying to push the

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:23.330
birthrate down.
 

00:09:23.330 --> 00:09:27.320
We'll talk about this later in
much more detail.

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:31.548
A provincial official gets the
word this is--

00:09:31.548 --> 00:09:34.615
we want your population growth
rate to be no more than whatever

00:09:34.615 --> 00:09:37.879
percentage and then he sends it
down to the prefecture and down.

00:09:37.879 --> 00:09:39.220
Do you think any of these
officials,

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:41.297
after the census,
are going send up information

00:09:41.297 --> 00:09:43.240
that they have not been doing
their job,

00:09:43.240 --> 00:09:44.889
that the birthrate is higher?
 

00:09:44.889 --> 00:09:49.240
No, so there's problems with
that.

00:09:49.240 --> 00:09:50.658
Who collects this data?
 

00:09:50.658 --> 00:09:54.190
Well luckily several--many
organizations collect the data

00:09:54.190 --> 00:09:55.639
but primarily the UN.
 

00:09:55.639 --> 00:09:58.529
Who owns the UN?
 

00:09:58.529 --> 00:10:04.782
Member countries,
and if you are,

00:10:04.782 --> 00:10:07.678
say,
a conservative religious

00:10:07.678 --> 00:10:10.991
country, and if the UN
demographer says that contrary

00:10:10.991 --> 00:10:14.010
to government statistics,
that there actually is a high

00:10:14.010 --> 00:10:16.028
rate of illegitimacy or abortion
in the country,

00:10:16.028 --> 00:10:19.308
all of which comes out of the
statistics,

00:10:19.308 --> 00:10:21.668
they're not going to allow that
to be published,

00:10:21.668 --> 00:10:24.851
so the UN has to sort of cut
some corners so that the

00:10:24.851 --> 00:10:28.340
countries from who it is
dependent on to get the data,

00:10:28.340 --> 00:10:33.029
will continue to send them the
data.

00:10:33.029 --> 00:10:36.029
In addition,
even when a country tries,

00:10:36.029 --> 00:10:37.440
there are something like 50
million--

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:40.683
birth registrations not done
everywhere in the world and

00:10:40.683 --> 00:10:43.279
there's something like 50
million babies,

00:10:43.279 --> 00:10:45.980
worldwide, who were never
registered,

00:10:45.980 --> 00:10:49.240
they don't exist on the
official registers,

00:10:49.240 --> 00:10:51.220
so when you try to do what
demographers do,

00:10:51.220 --> 00:10:55.178
you have a count of--a count of
a census in one year,

00:10:55.178 --> 00:10:57.250
you have a count of a census in
a later year,

00:10:57.250 --> 00:10:59.629
in between you have a list of
births and deaths,

00:10:59.629 --> 00:11:01.480
supposedly both births are
registered and deaths are

00:11:01.480 --> 00:11:03.960
registered,
and you see is this reasonable?

00:11:03.960 --> 00:11:06.404
Is the difference accounted for
by births, deaths,

00:11:06.404 --> 00:11:09.399
and migration if you have
reasonable amounts of migration.

00:11:09.399 --> 00:11:16.085
If millions of the babies are
just not registered you can't

00:11:16.085 --> 00:11:22.308
check things that way,
so there's a lot of problems.

00:11:22.308 --> 00:11:25.764
Another thing is that in many,
many countries there's conflict

00:11:25.764 --> 00:11:29.254
between different groups,
we've talked about Democratic,

00:11:29.254 --> 00:11:31.350
Republican in the United
States.

00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:35.452
In Nigeria, in Sudan,
there's a huge conflict between

00:11:35.452 --> 00:11:39.791
the Muslim populations in the
north and the Christian or

00:11:39.791 --> 00:11:42.710
Animist populations in the
south.

00:11:42.710 --> 00:11:46.154
You may or may not recall the
Biafra War in Nigeria,

00:11:46.154 --> 00:11:49.529
a huge war between
basically--over oil--but between

00:11:49.529 --> 00:11:52.570
the Muslim north and the
Christian south;

00:11:52.570 --> 00:11:57.196
millions of deaths and millions
of deaths now currently in Sudan

00:11:57.196 --> 00:11:59.840
over something of a similar
issue.

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:03.839
When censuses in ethnically or
religiously split countries are

00:12:03.839 --> 00:12:05.923
taken,
the key event is the ratio,

00:12:05.923 --> 00:12:09.019
the key outcome that everybody
wants to know is the ratio

00:12:09.019 --> 00:12:12.105
between how many Christians,
how many Muslims,

00:12:12.105 --> 00:12:14.428
how many this,
how many that.

00:12:14.428 --> 00:12:21.520
And so the censuses get totally
distorted by people trying to

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:28.139
raise their numbers and lower
everyone else's numbers.

00:12:28.139 --> 00:12:33.003
Before the Biafra War there was
apparently a reasonably accurate

00:12:33.003 --> 00:12:37.302
census in 1952 to 1953,
then the Biafra War intervened,

00:12:37.302 --> 00:12:41.370
and the next several censuses
were very controversial.

00:12:41.370 --> 00:12:45.621
So the accepted official
figures, in Nigeria,

00:12:45.621 --> 00:12:50.356
were 88.5 million people,
but the World Bank said,

00:12:50.356 --> 00:12:54.320
no, that's wrong,
102 million people.

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:57.889
The United Nations:
120 million people.

00:12:57.889 --> 00:13:00.998
So, basically,
for a country as big and as

00:13:00.998 --> 00:13:05.318
important as Nigeria for their
last census we have figures

00:13:05.318 --> 00:13:09.110
ranging between 88.5 million and
120 million,

00:13:09.110 --> 00:13:15.250
a 50% uncertainty for Nigeria,
so big.

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:19.740
The point of this initial part,
point one,

00:13:19.740 --> 00:13:22.480
is that even the simplest
numbers like headcounts,

00:13:22.480 --> 00:13:24.657
we're not doing anything fancy,
we're just trying to count how

00:13:24.657 --> 00:13:27.215
many people there are,
1,2, 3,4, 5,

00:13:27.215 --> 00:13:35.267
there are systematic errors and
very often those errors are

00:13:35.267 --> 00:13:37.350
intentional.
 

00:13:37.350 --> 00:13:40.716
Now all of these numbers--well
I say when I described these

00:13:40.716 --> 00:13:43.269
numbers and I probably won't do
it enough.

00:13:43.269 --> 00:13:47.695
When I put up a demographic
number it should almost always

00:13:47.695 --> 00:13:51.303
be qualified by,
'and there are large and

00:13:51.303 --> 00:13:56.460
unknown error bars,' but we
don't have error bars for it.

00:13:56.460 --> 00:13:59.745
Various organizations collect
all this data and this is called

00:13:59.745 --> 00:14:03.053
the Population Reference Bureau,
which is a source of statistics

00:14:03.053 --> 00:14:06.942
