extreme difference.

00:30:04.990 --> 00:30:07.528
Here is what's left,
so this is the United States.

00:30:07.528 --> 00:30:11.500
This is the deaths per 1,000,
the age of the people,

00:30:11.500 --> 00:30:13.730
and here's what's left of the
infant mortality,

00:30:13.730 --> 00:30:16.338
it's still more dangerous to be
an infant than later,

00:30:16.338 --> 00:30:19.619
but there's virtually--you
can't even see the death rate

00:30:19.619 --> 00:30:23.973
through the middle years,
but then boom it goes up as you

00:30:23.973 --> 00:30:26.400
get on into the older ages.
 

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:30.750
Indeed, the death rate is
completely sensitive to your age

00:30:30.750 --> 00:30:33.955
distribution,
a country that has more young

00:30:33.955 --> 00:30:37.009
people will have a lower death
rate.

00:30:37.009 --> 00:30:40.073
A country that has a high
birthrate will have more young

00:30:40.073 --> 00:30:42.458
people,
will have a lower death rate,

00:30:42.458 --> 00:30:45.358
so what you're seeing in that
anomaly there,

00:30:45.358 --> 00:30:49.500
what looked like an anomaly,
is basically that Mexico has a

00:30:49.500 --> 00:30:51.568
higher birthrate of people.
 

00:30:51.568 --> 00:30:56.430
This funny thing,
you happen to be born young and

00:30:56.430 --> 00:31:02.000
you die old, and so that is the
explanation for that.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:05.310
Any time--almost any
demographic number that you want

00:31:05.310 --> 00:31:07.720
to interpret,
marriage rates,

00:31:07.720 --> 00:31:11.567
birthrates, death rates,
fertility rates,

00:31:11.567 --> 00:31:16.151
almost everything of interest
is affected by the age

00:31:16.151 --> 00:31:17.588
distribution.
 

00:31:17.588 --> 00:31:21.996
In understanding demographic
statistics, the most important

00:31:21.996 --> 00:31:24.960
thing is always the age
distribution.

00:31:24.960 --> 00:31:27.410
You always have to pay
attention to that,

00:31:27.410 --> 00:31:32.246
and later on I'll show you one
of the mechanisms for paying

00:31:32.246 --> 00:31:34.432
attention--
for getting

00:31:34.432 --> 00:31:40.348
statistics--adjusting statistics
for the age distribution.

00:31:40.348 --> 00:31:42.960
How--first let's just look at
it.

00:31:42.960 --> 00:31:47.390
So here is the easiest way of
looking at an age distribution.

00:31:47.390 --> 00:31:50.192
What you have here,
this is for Germany and the

00:31:50.192 --> 00:31:53.519
pink is the old--
this is 1989 when East and West

00:31:53.519 --> 00:31:56.660
Germany were still split,
so this is the German

00:31:56.660 --> 00:31:58.930
Democratic Republic,
East Germany,

00:31:58.930 --> 00:32:02.699
the pink is East Germans and
the dark is the Federal

00:32:02.699 --> 00:32:05.240
Republic,
West Germany,

00:32:05.240 --> 00:32:11.568
and on the left is men and on
the right is female,

00:32:11.568 --> 00:32:16.292
male and female,
and what this graph says is

00:32:16.292 --> 00:32:19.753
that every year--
so this is age zero,

00:32:19.753 --> 00:32:24.423
you're just born,
to age 100, that every year

00:32:24.423 --> 00:32:28.910
they ask how many people are
there?

00:32:28.910 --> 00:32:32.420
How many kids are there between
age zero and one?

00:32:32.420 --> 00:32:34.575
Well there's so many males and
so many females,

00:32:34.575 --> 00:32:37.338
this number in East Germany,
this number in West Germany.

00:32:37.338 --> 00:32:41.278
You can go through every age
and just count from your census

00:32:41.278 --> 00:32:45.348
the number of people at that age
and draw it out like this.

00:32:45.348 --> 00:32:48.799
It's a wonderful huge amount of
information in a single graph;

00:32:48.799 --> 00:32:50.670
you can see all kinds of things.
 

00:32:50.670 --> 00:32:55.090
This is World War I,
the people born during World

00:32:55.090 --> 00:32:57.473
War I,
they're almost all gone,

00:32:57.473 --> 00:33:01.102
but here's the ones from World
War II and look at the big

00:33:01.102 --> 00:33:02.009
difference.
 

00:33:02.009 --> 00:33:04.019
Here's your females.
 

00:33:04.019 --> 00:33:06.049
Here's your males.
 

00:33:06.049 --> 00:33:11.079
What's the difference?
 

00:33:11.079 --> 00:33:14.824
War deaths;
the men are in the Army and the

00:33:14.824 --> 00:33:17.932
get shot up on the Russian
front, so you have many more

00:33:17.932 --> 00:33:19.200
females then males.
 

00:33:19.200 --> 00:33:22.618
It's partially that women live
older also but this case in

00:33:22.618 --> 00:33:26.380
Germany is almost exclusive--
is overwhelmingly the deaths

00:33:26.380 --> 00:33:28.782
from World War I,
here there's still some

00:33:28.782 --> 00:33:32.855
females, there's no males,
and then the deaths from World

00:33:32.855 --> 00:33:33.578
War II.
 

00:33:33.578 --> 00:33:36.957
You can see the birth deficit,
these are people who would have

00:33:36.957 --> 00:33:39.673
been born during World War I,
these were adults,

00:33:39.673 --> 00:33:41.769
fighting age adults during
World War I.

00:33:41.769 --> 00:33:45.453
These would have been born
while the men were away so they

00:33:45.453 --> 00:33:47.068
didn't have any babies.
 

00:33:47.068 --> 00:33:52.301
They had very few babies during
World War I and the same thing

00:33:52.301 --> 00:33:56.932
you see for World War II,
and you see again the deficit

00:33:56.932 --> 00:33:59.848
of--well we talked about that.
 

00:33:59.848 --> 00:34:03.978
You can see that,
then you can see there's a post

00:34:03.978 --> 00:34:07.217
war baby boom,
after the deficit in World War

00:34:07.217 --> 00:34:10.358
II people make up for it and
more than make up for the

00:34:10.358 --> 00:34:13.699
deficit,
so you have this huge bulge in

00:34:13.699 --> 00:34:16.739
population,
both males and females,

00:34:16.739 --> 00:34:19.925
but now balanced,
more or less equal numbers of

00:34:19.925 --> 00:34:23.103
males and females,
and then you get the baby bust

00:34:23.103 --> 00:34:25.510
and you get a little echo
effect,

00:34:25.510 --> 00:34:27.788
so there's
variations--fluctuations in

00:34:27.788 --> 00:34:30.202
population--
almost every country

00:34:30.202 --> 00:34:34.625
has--Western country has these
kind of data plus the Asian

00:34:34.625 --> 00:34:38.349
countries that were involved in
World War II.

00:34:38.349 --> 00:34:44.289
You can see it's a wonderful
way of understanding a country.

00:34:44.289 --> 00:34:55.639
Now this is India--the census
of India, that's a weird one.

00:34:55.639 --> 00:34:56.989
What the heck is going on there?
 

00:35:04.989 --> 00:35:06.871
That's weird,
so what it is,

00:35:06.871 --> 00:35:09.309
is people don't know their
ages,

00:35:09.309 --> 00:35:12.309
they're innumerate,
and so it gets counted every

00:35:12.309 --> 00:35:15.282
five or ten years,
so here's a five year or a ten

00:35:15.282 --> 00:35:15.989
year period.
 

00:35:15.989 --> 00:35:18.621
They know their ages
approximately,

00:35:18.621 --> 00:35:22.490
to approximately a certain
year, they don't know it

00:35:22.490 --> 00:35:23.420
exactly.
 

00:35:23.420 --> 00:35:26.318
It's not important,
in a pre-industrial country

00:35:26.318 --> 00:35:29.659
their exact age is not all that
terribly important.

00:35:29.659 --> 00:35:34.262
You get this--that's called age
heaping, that when you get a

00:35:34.262 --> 00:35:37.849
large excess in five or ten year
increments.

00:35:37.849 --> 00:35:39.666
My own father,
who was an immigrant,

00:35:39.666 --> 00:35:40.860
did not know his age.
 

00:35:40.860 --> 00:35:43.936
There was--he was born in
either 1904 or 1907 because he

00:35:43.936 --> 00:35:47.404
even had a birth certificate but
it was in the Russian Cyrillic

00:35:47.404 --> 00:35:50.090
characters and the four looks
like a seven,

00:35:50.090 --> 00:35:56.057
so he and my mother argued
constantly over how old he

00:35:56.057 --> 00:35:57.780
actually was.
 

00:35:57.780 --> 00:36:00.952
Even countries that have had a
long--European have the same

00:36:00.952 --> 00:36:01.389
thing.
 

00:36:01.389 --> 00:36:05.684
Here is the Soviet Union from
their 1937 census and here again

00:36:05.684 --> 00:36:08.429
you get this same age heaping
effect.

00:36:08.429 --> 00:36:11.570
Not quite as extreme as India
but very clearly here,

00:36:11.570 --> 00:36:15.409
and to a degree worse with
women then with men,

00:36:15.409 --> 00:36:18.179
because women are less
educated, see the big bars here,

00:36:18.179 --> 00:36:21.452
the small bars here,
and in principle it should be

00:36:21.452 --> 00:36:25.260
getting less with younger people
it should be clearer,

00:36:25.260 --> 00:36:28.717
and you certainly do get rid of
these extreme on certain of

00:36:28.717 --> 00:36:33.141
these but it's not--
it's persisting into the 1930s

00:36:33.141 --> 00:36:39.675
this 'I don't know how old I am
except within a five or ten year

00:36:39.675 --> 00:36:40.920
bracket.'
 

00:36:40.920 --> 00:36:48.179
Here's another weirdo,
what's that?

00:36:48.179 --> 00:36:51.056
Just to show you that you can
immediately, once you get used

00:36:51.056 --> 00:36:53.882
to this, immediately tell an
awful lot about a country from

00:36:53.882 --> 00:36:54.809
an age pyramid.
 

00:37:01.949 --> 00:37:05.420
Anybody from Arizona?
 

00:37:05.420 --> 00:37:06.940
Nobody from--what?
 

00:37:06.940 --> 00:37:10.210
Student: 
&gt;

00:37:10.210 --> 00:37:13.661
Prof: It's Sun City,
Arizona which is a retirement

00:37:13.661 --> 00:37:16.250
community and they don't allow
anybody--

00:37:16.250 --> 00:37:18.980
I think most of these have an
age limit of 50,

00:37:18.980 --> 00:37:22.719
you have to be at least 55,
so this is the retirement age,

00:37:22.719 --> 00:37:25.362
and where my mother lives in
Century Village in West Palm

00:37:25.362 --> 00:37:27.983
Beach looks like this --
Florida looks like that,

00:37:27.983 --> 00:37:30.911
various retired--
California has retirement

00:37:30.911 --> 00:37:33.170
villages they look like that.
 

00:37:33.170 --> 00:37:37.833
These population pyramids are
wonderful with lots of

00:37:37.833 --> 00:37:43.501
information packed into this and
from seeing these pyramids you

00:37:43.501 --> 00:37:48.440
can tell a lot about the
socioeconomic character of the

00:37:48.440 --> 00:37:53.744
countries because we know that
the poor countries have less

00:37:53.744 --> 00:37:57.639
literacy,
etc., etc., and they have

00:37:57.639 --> 00:38:02.860
higher birthrates and so we'll
look at what that looks like

00:38:02.860 --> 00:38:04.030
right now.
 

00:38:04.030 --> 00:38:08.590
Here are two of these
population pyramids and here

00:38:08.590 --> 00:38:11.146
is--
you saw in those the splitting

00:38:11.146 --> 00:38:14.010
of the world into more developed
regions,

00:38:14.010 --> 00:38:16.480
and less developed regions.
 

00:38:16.480 --> 00:38:19.360
What do you notice right away?
 

00:38:19.360 --> 00:38:22.623
The total area under this,
so this is now five-year age

00:38:22.623 --> 00:38:27.068
heaps rather than single year,
so between zero and four is

00:38:27.068 --> 00:38:29.000
this amount,
or this amount,

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:31.820
so it's the area under this is
how many total people there are.

00:38:31.820 --> 00:38:34.489
One you see there's a lot less
area here,

00:38:34.489 --> 00:38:38.184
a lot less people,
the less developed regions are

00:38:38.184 --> 00:38:42.880
the bulk of the world but also
the shape is very different.

00:38:42.880 --> 00:38:49.282
Here in the developed regions
you have a more or less similar

00:38:49.282 --> 00:38:52.590
number of people in all ages.
 

00:38:52.590 --> 00:38:54.670
It's not exactly that way.
 

00:38:54.670 --> 00:38:58.083
Of course at the old age people
are dying and that starts about

00:38:58.083 --> 00:39:01.168
here in the 50s and then
accelerates and there's very few

00:39:01.168 --> 00:39:04.072
left,
so it narrows here and also

00:39:04.072 --> 00:39:09.476
it's narrowing down here because
the birthrate in the developed

00:39:09.476 --> 00:39:13.833
countries is now below
replacement level and so the

00:39:13.833 --> 00:39:19.324
pyramids are getting to be fewer
people in the younger ages then

00:39:19.324 --> 00:39:21.940
there are older people.
 

00:39:21.940 --> 00:39:26.409
Contrast that with less
developed parts of the world and

00:39:26.409 --> 00:39:30.391
you see that there's more and
more younger people,

00:39:30.391 --> 00:39:34.050
each age cohort has more and
more people.

00:39:34.050 --> 00:39:40.282
You can look at an individual
country, and this is a clearer

00:39:40.282 --> 00:39:41.340
example.
 

00:39:41.340 --> 00:39:44.429
This is Nigeria as far as we
can tell from their census,

00:39:44.429 --> 00:39:48.159
but they--you can tell an age
distribution and this is now

00:39:48.159 --> 00:39:51.170
percent rather than total from
sub-samples,

00:39:51.170 --> 00:39:53.318
you don't need to count
absolutely everybody to

00:39:53.318 --> 00:39:55.280
understand what the age
distribution is.

00:39:55.280 --> 00:39:59.864
Here is a 50-year change,
there's not one--it's not

00:39:59.864 --> 00:40:01.789
changing very much.
 

00:40:01.789 --> 00:40:04.876
This is what it was in 1975,
they know more or less what it

00:40:04.876 --> 00:40:08.070
is now, and they're projecting
it out to 2005--;I'm sorry.

00:40:08.070 --> 00:40:12.920
This is pretty current and it
looks about the same,

00:40:12.920 --> 00:40:16.117
and vastly as you go in this
case, as you go to younger and

00:40:16.117 --> 00:40:21.628
younger people,
vastly more children than older

00:40:21.628 --> 00:40:22.650
folks.
 

00:40:22.650 --> 00:40:26.530
So what's happening here--see
what the ages are here,

00:40:26.530 --> 00:40:30.657
especially in Nigeria,
15 to 45, these are the ages in

00:40:30.657 --> 00:40:35.487
which women are giving birth and
this number of women is giving

00:40:35.487 --> 00:40:40.030
birth to more than two children,
they're more then replacing

00:40:40.030 --> 00:40:43.594
themselves,
so each bar is bigger than the

00:40:43.594 --> 00:40:45.806
last,
and some of this in-swing,

00:40:45.806 --> 00:40:48.219
especially this is Sub-Saharan
Africa,

00:40:48.219 --> 00:40:51.271
some of this reduction is
infant mortality and child

00:40:51.271 --> 00:40:51.989
mortality.
 

00:40:51.989 --> 00:40:54.657
Some of the differences,
especially between this bar and

00:40:54.657 --> 00:40:57.230
this bar, that's in there,
but it's a small effect.

00:40:57.230 --> 00:41:05.398
The major effect is that every
generation is bigger and they

00:41:05.398 --> 00:41:10.659
produce more and more children
here.

00:41:10.659 --> 00:41:22.079
Now--so when you look at
how--what's going to evolve in

00:41:22.079 --> 00:41:28.606
the future--
so here is your women who are

00:41:28.606 --> 00:41:32.148
40 to 45,
that's this bunch of women and

00:41:32.148 --> 00:41:34.739
women on this side,
so that's the number of women.

00:41:34.739 --> 00:41:38.320
They're producing part of these
children.

00:41:38.320 --> 00:41:41.286
In another five years,
if you look at this five years

00:41:41.286 --> 00:41:44.311
later, these women who were 40
to 45 are now 45 to 50,

00:41:44.311 --> 00:41:46.309
no more fertility,
pretty much.

00:41:46.309 --> 00:41:49.510
In Nigeria they're not using a
lot of IVF and everything.

00:41:49.510 --> 00:41:53.143
So they have stopped
reproducing but that cohort of

00:41:53.143 --> 00:41:57.358
that size is being replaced by
the ones of this size coming

00:41:57.358 --> 00:42:01.001
into fertile ages,
so women that were 10 to 15 are

00:42:01.001 --> 00:42:04.309
becoming 15 to 20 and starting
their childbearing,

00:42:04.309 --> 00:42:07.492
when women that are 40 to 45
which have not so much

00:42:07.492 --> 00:42:10.329
childbearing left,
are going out of existence and

00:42:10.329 --> 00:42:12.030
stopping childbearing
absolutely.

00:42:12.030 --> 00:42:15.235
The number of women,
the number of child bearers is

00:42:15.235 --> 00:42:16.840
increasing drastically.
 

00:42:16.840 --> 00:42:19.039
In this case,
it looks ballpark like there

00:42:19.039 --> 00:42:22.150
are twice as many women coming
into reproductive age as are

00:42:22.150 --> 00:42:26.554
leaving reproductive age,
each year, each five years

00:42:26.554 --> 00:42:29.780
however you want to count it.
 

00:42:29.780 --> 00:42:33.882
The number of childbearing
women is increasing

00:42:33.882 --> 00:42:35.250
tremendously.
 

00:42:35.250 --> 00:42:40.659
The result of that is--here's
another comparison,

00:42:40.659 --> 00:42:44.748
whereas in the west,
in developed countries the

00:42:44.748 --> 00:42:50.079
number of 40 to 45 year olds is
not enormously different then

00:42:50.079 --> 00:42:52.480
the number to 15 to 19.
 

00:42:52.480 --> 00:42:55.541
So the women that are leaving
reproductive ages are more or

00:42:55.541 --> 00:42:58.655
less replaced by the women that
are coming into reproductive

00:42:58.655 --> 00:42:59.130
ages.
 

00:42:59.130 --> 00:43:01.340
Of course with population
decline,

00:43:01.340 --> 00:43:05.063
eventually you get fewer women
coming into reproductive age in

00:43:05.063 --> 00:43:07.690
developed countries then are
leaving it,

00:43:07.690 --> 00:43:10.110
so that you have fewer child
bearers,

00:43:10.110 --> 00:43:13.963
so this phenomenon can--if your
population is increasing the

00:43:13.963 --> 00:43:16.380
problem gets more and more
severe,

00:43:16.380 --> 00:43:18.940
if it's decreasing the problem
gets more and more severe.

00:43:18.940 --> 00:43:24.108
There's a positive feedback on
this with your number of child

00:43:24.108 --> 00:43:27.469
bearers either growing or
decreasing.

00:43:27.469 --> 00:43:34.244
Here is in billions--the number
of women of childbearing age in

00:43:34.244 --> 00:43:39.599
the world, and it just keeps
increasing, right?

00:43:39.599 --> 00:43:42.960
What you may be aware of,
I haven't really talked about

00:43:42.960 --> 00:43:45.626
this much yet,
because it's in my next

00:43:45.626 --> 00:43:48.840
lecture, here is the birthrate
in the world,

00:43:48.840 --> 00:43:50.599
children per women.
 

00:43:50.599 --> 00:43:53.570
The birthrate has been coming
down.

00:43:53.570 --> 00:43:56.960
Two opposite things are
happening in the world.

00:43:56.960 --> 00:44:01.742
The number of childbearing
women is going up but the number

00:44:01.742 --> 00:44:05.949
of children that each of them
have is going down.

00:44:05.949 --> 00:44:10.141
They predict optimistically
that by 2050 it'll reach about

00:44:10.141 --> 00:44:13.599
replacement of about two
children per women,

00:44:13.599 --> 00:44:16.570
but it's not there,
we're not there yet,

00:44:16.570 --> 00:44:25.590
we're almost double-- we're way
above that now.

00:44:25.590 --> 00:44:29.630
The result of this number of
women rising,

00:44:29.630 --> 00:44:34.559
their rate of childbearing
decreasing is that the number of

00:44:34.559 --> 00:44:36.451
births,
you sort of multiply those two

00:44:36.451 --> 00:44:38.779
out,
the number of births is

00:44:38.779 --> 00:44:44.309
expected to continue increasing
for the predictable future.

00:44:44.309 --> 00:44:49.684
That the absolute number of
births will increase as a result

00:44:49.684 --> 00:44:52.599
of these two crossing factors.
 

00:44:52.599 --> 00:44:56.628
Now the birthrate is coming
down and it eventually,

00:44:56.628 --> 00:45:01.059
let's presume in the future,
gets to be two children.

00:45:01.059 --> 00:45:02.190
What then happens?
 

00:45:02.190 --> 00:45:06.981
You still have a pyramid like
this but now it starts

00:45:06.981 --> 00:45:11.114
flattening out,
but it flattens out--I should

00:45:11.114 --> 00:45:13.369
not do this by hand.
 

00:45:13.369 --> 00:45:17.360
In fact I want to go to this
graph.

00:45:17.360 --> 00:45:21.208
It shows this--this is what's
actually predicted to happen,

00:45:21.208 --> 00:45:24.992
so this is again developing
countries and this is the kind

00:45:24.992 --> 00:45:27.050
of pyramid that we've seen.
 

00:45:27.050 --> 00:45:33.489
This one goes back to 1985 with
this broadly increasing thing.

00:45:33.489 --> 00:45:36.603
It's basically a triangle,
you can think of it is as a

00:45:36.603 --> 00:45:37.250
triangle.
 

00:45:37.250 --> 00:45:40.085
If immediately,
God sticks his finger out of

00:45:40.085 --> 00:45:43.646
heaven and says two children,
and even more surprising,

00:45:43.646 --> 00:45:45.889
people obey him,
what happens?

00:45:45.889 --> 00:45:49.018
This is the number of children,
people that there are there,

00:45:49.018 --> 00:45:54.827
that the population pyramid
will grow up but with this as a

00:45:54.827 --> 00:45:57.436
base,
so that it will become square

00:45:57.436 --> 00:45:59.679
but there will be this many
people.

00:45:59.679 --> 00:46:04.590
You go from a triangle to a
rectangle with the same base.

00:46:04.590 --> 00:46:05.119
Can you see that?
 

00:46:05.119 --> 00:46:09.362
The number of people is the
area inside that and you have

00:46:09.362 --> 00:46:11.655
the same base,
you go from a triangle to

00:46:11.655 --> 00:46:14.677
rectangle--
remember from high school

00:46:14.677 --> 00:46:17.420
geometry what the area is?
 

00:46:17.420 --> 00:46:19.239
It doubles.
 

00:46:19.239 --> 00:46:21.833
Because, if you have a triangle
and you go square,

00:46:21.833 --> 00:46:24.800
you just flip that--half the
triangle over and you've got

00:46:24.800 --> 00:46:26.230
that many people again.
 

00:46:26.230 --> 00:46:30.789
If a miracle happens and
fertility stops dead right now

00:46:30.789 --> 00:46:34.757
and we go immediately to two
children per woman,

00:46:34.757 --> 00:46:38.809
the population doubles before
it stabilizes.

00:46:38.809 --> 00:46:41.360
What this shows you,
of course is that miracle is

00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:42.530
not going to happen.
 

00:46:42.530 --> 00:46:46.766
This is quite optimistic and is
already not the case,

00:46:46.766 --> 00:46:49.619
that the base will also
increase.

00:46:49.619 --> 00:46:51.949
Since the population is still
increasing,

00:46:51.949 --> 00:46:55.300
the base will increase,
and yes it will get more

00:46:55.300 --> 00:46:58.670
rectangular,
but even by 2025 it won't yet

00:46:58.670 --> 00:47:01.125
be rectangular,
so that you will,

00:47:01.125 --> 00:47:06.153
on this kind of projection,
more than double the population

00:47:06.153 --> 00:47:12.340
from 1985 because the base is
growing as well as you're rising

00:47:12.340 --> 00:47:12.949
up.
 

00:47:12.949 --> 00:47:21.280
There's an expectation of quite
a lot of population increase

00:47:21.280 --> 00:47:22.268
left.
 

00:47:22.268 --> 00:47:25.789
This whole phenomenon where
because you--

00:47:25.789 --> 00:47:29.454
once you start having an
increasing population you're

00:47:29.454 --> 00:47:31.472
going to--
the population is going to keep

00:47:31.472 --> 00:47:33.742
increasing because there's more
and more child bearers unless

00:47:33.742 --> 00:47:35.710
something drastic happens to the
fertility rate,

00:47:35.710 --> 00:47:38.739
it's called population momentum
because you're sort of moving in

00:47:38.739 --> 00:47:41.050
a certain direction of
increasing population,

00:47:41.050 --> 00:47:42.789
it just continues.
 

00:47:42.789 --> 00:47:46.128
The same thing happens as
you'll see in the next lecture

00:47:46.128 --> 00:47:49.067
with population decreasing,
and when population decreases

00:47:49.067 --> 00:47:51.380
you have fewer and fewer child
bearers in each generation,

00:47:51.380 --> 00:47:56.309
as say Japan now or Singapore,
and so unless the birth rate

00:47:56.309 --> 00:48:01.579
increases tremendously you'll
have fewer and fewer children.

00:48:01.579 --> 00:48:06.067
What this shows you is that,
if there's immediate

00:48:06.067 --> 00:48:08.501
replacement,
this kind of miracle that

00:48:08.501 --> 00:48:10.704
everything--
that everybody comes to just

00:48:10.704 --> 00:48:14.588
two children immediately,
then the population would be

00:48:14.588 --> 00:48:17.679
this, so this effect is all
momentum.

00:48:17.679 --> 00:48:21.820
All of this increase,
from where we are now to up

00:48:21.820 --> 00:48:24.009
here,
is just a momentum effect,

00:48:24.009 --> 00:48:27.469
just the fact that there's more
and more children coming into

00:48:27.469 --> 00:48:31.159
reproductive age and that takes
a very long time to work out.

00:48:31.159 --> 00:48:34.686
Then the fact that there's in
fact -- they're not going

00:48:34.686 --> 00:48:38.409
immediately to two children,
not immediate replacement.

00:48:38.409 --> 00:48:41.487
This is the United Nations
guess as to what's going to

00:48:41.487 --> 00:48:42.010
happen.
 

00:48:42.010 --> 00:48:45.780
The actual population is
projected to go like this.

00:48:45.780 --> 00:48:50.635
If everybody immediately goes
to two children you get this

00:48:50.635 --> 00:48:52.170
population rise.
 

00:48:52.170 --> 00:48:55.059
What is actually expected is
somewhat more,

00:48:55.059 --> 00:48:58.985
so huge amount of what's
happening with population future

00:48:58.985 --> 00:49:02.599
is already determined,
it's already momentum is in

00:49:02.599 --> 00:49:06.800
there and even if birthrates
really come down very rapidly,

00:49:06.800 --> 00:49:17.768
the world's population is going
to continue increasing.

00:49:17.768 --> 00:49:20.059
That's sort of an important
thing to remember.

00:49:20.059 --> 00:49:27.498
In the world the fertility is
decreasing, the population is

00:49:27.498 --> 00:49:33.268
increasing and those are not
canceling out.

00:49:33.268 --> 00:49:36.967
From 1985 the prediction was
that the world population would

00:49:36.967 --> 00:49:39.126
somewhat double,
we've made some progress

00:49:39.126 --> 00:49:42.784
between there,
but still we have 6.7 billion

00:49:42.784 --> 00:49:48.605
now and the expectation is
something like 50% more people

00:49:48.605 --> 00:49:54.530
on earth in 2050 and perhaps
continuing to increase beyond

00:49:54.530 --> 00:49:55.570
that.
 

00:49:55.570 --> 00:50:00.329
Huge amount of momentum
effects, here is--

00:50:00.329 --> 00:50:05.471
let me go back--this is
Mauritius, an island in the

00:50:05.471 --> 00:50:10.715
Indian Ocean and it's one of the
examples of a small

00:50:10.715 --> 00:50:16.679
underdeveloped country that had
a very surprising fertility

00:50:16.679 --> 00:50:18.119
decline.
 

00:50:18.119 --> 00:50:22.661
This is probably the influenza
epidemic here,

00:50:22.661 --> 00:50:28.751
but starting in around--right
after World War II in the late

00:50:28.751 --> 00:50:32.570
1940s, it's death rate fell
down;

00:50:32.570 --> 00:50:35.909
modern public health comes in
to Mauritius,

00:50:35.909 --> 00:50:39.010
so the death rate falls
dramatically.

00:50:39.010 --> 00:50:42.422
Then this fits the standard
characterization of the

00:50:42.422 --> 00:50:44.130
demographic transition.
 

00:50:44.130 --> 00:50:47.369
About 20 years later,
about one generation later,

00:50:47.369 --> 00:50:49.612
people learn,
well we don't have to have so

00:50:49.612 --> 00:50:51.909
many children because they're
not dying,

00:50:51.909 --> 00:51:01.460
and the birthrate comes down
thereafter and population growth

00:51:01.460 --> 00:51:03.530
is in here.
 

00:51:03.530 --> 00:51:07.929
This is a country that did
well, that starting fairly early

00:51:07.929 --> 00:51:11.949
for a developing country,
1951 say, their birthrate is

00:51:11.949 --> 00:51:13.239
falling down.
 

00:51:13.239 --> 00:51:20.324
They really sort of got it
under control and--but look at

00:51:20.324 --> 00:51:21.210
this.
 

00:51:21.210 --> 00:51:29.931
So this is the birth--the total
fertility rate which is a birth

00:51:29.931 --> 00:51:33.733
rate here,
and it stays stable and then it

00:51:33.733 --> 00:51:36.409
starts falling down quite
significantly,

00:51:36.409 --> 00:51:39.760
but look at here's total
population size.

00:51:39.760 --> 00:51:42.639
You don't even see a change;
all momentum.

00:51:42.639 --> 00:51:48.248
Here the birthrate has started
dropping in 1965 and now we're

00:51:48.248 --> 00:51:53.485
25 years later and you don't see
hardly any change in the

00:51:53.485 --> 00:51:56.010
population growth rate.
 

00:51:56.010 --> 00:51:58.994
That's what we talk about by
the momentum effect that because

00:51:58.994 --> 00:52:01.137
at this time,
before they drop their

00:52:01.137 --> 00:52:04.813
fertility, at this time there
were so many more children than

00:52:04.813 --> 00:52:08.489
older people that the number of
women child bearers just kept

00:52:08.489 --> 00:52:11.425
increasing and increasing,
and increasing,

00:52:11.425 --> 00:52:15.202
so even though fertility drops
the number of children stays

00:52:15.202 --> 00:52:17.155
high,
even gets higher,

00:52:17.155 --> 00:52:20.530
and the population just keeps
increasing.

00:52:20.530 --> 00:52:22.947
It's a very,
very strong effect and the

00:52:22.947 --> 00:52:25.940
number of--and it's not
flattened out there yet,

00:52:25.940 --> 00:52:27.150
25 years later.
 

00:52:27.150 --> 00:52:32.260
This is a projection of how
long does it take before it

00:52:32.260 --> 00:52:33.679
flattens out.
 

00:52:33.679 --> 00:52:39.764
This is the first one,
the first box is the year--this

00:52:39.764 --> 00:52:45.619
is our current size as of
whatever year this was.

00:52:45.619 --> 00:52:49.070
By 2030--this is the United
States.

00:52:49.070 --> 00:52:55.840
This is the number of people,
so this graph was made in--

00:52:55.840 --> 00:52:59.083
it doesn't say the date but our
population will increase

00:52:59.083 --> 00:53:02.623
somewhat by 2030 and this really
is ignoring the changes that

00:53:02.623 --> 00:53:06.280
have happened with immigration
and so forth that we will--

00:53:06.280 --> 00:53:10.132
we reach two child--if our
fertility comes down we reach

00:53:10.132 --> 00:53:13.846
two child in 2030 and we
stabilize because we have not

00:53:13.846 --> 00:53:17.699
had a rapidly expanding
population so we stabilize right

00:53:17.699 --> 00:53:18.469
away.
 

00:53:18.469 --> 00:53:22.639
Nigeria, which you saw,
current population,

00:53:22.639 --> 00:53:27.110
it's supposed to but some
optimistic assumptions reach two

00:53:27.110 --> 00:53:30.170
children per women in the year
2035,

00:53:30.170 --> 00:53:36.090
but then it doesn't stabilize
until 115 years later at again a

00:53:36.090 --> 00:53:38.809
much increased population.
 

00:53:38.809 --> 00:53:42.400
In the case of Nigeria,
after it reaches two child per

00:53:42.400 --> 00:53:44.735
woman,
after it reaches replacement

00:53:44.735 --> 00:53:46.869
level,
it takes another 115 years

00:53:46.869 --> 00:53:49.329
before population actually
stabilizes.

00:53:49.329 --> 00:53:51.780
This is Bangladesh, 125 years.
 

00:53:51.780 --> 00:53:58.081
This is Iran, 110 years;
Iran has had a big crash,

00:53:58.081 --> 00:54:00.119
we'll talk about that and its
population.

00:54:00.119 --> 00:54:04.893
Brazil 145 years,
it takes an enormous amount of

00:54:04.893 --> 00:54:10.985
time for momentum to work itself
out after the fertility rate

00:54:10.985 --> 00:54:12.510
comes down.
 

00:54:12.510 --> 00:54:17.422
It's quite striking,
and that's the reason why we

00:54:17.422 --> 00:54:22.539
expect so much more population
growth to happen.

00:54:22.539 --> 00:54:26.202
Again, you can look at an
individual country,

00:54:26.202 --> 00:54:30.199
and this is Algeria,
and look at what Algeria has

00:54:30.199 --> 00:54:34.780
done between--in 20 years:
that's an enormous rate.

00:54:34.780 --> 00:54:37.980
Here's its crude birthrate,
it's--crude means not corrected

00:54:37.980 --> 00:54:40.871
for age or anything,
just take 1,000 people,

00:54:40.871 --> 00:54:44.400
how many babies were there for
that 1,000 people.

00:54:44.400 --> 00:54:48.416
In 1965 there were 50 and it
dropped to 38,

00:54:48.416 --> 00:54:52.530
a very large drop and it's a
drop of 24%.

00:54:52.530 --> 00:54:56.757
They cut their birthrate by a
quarter, that's 25% in 20 years,

00:54:56.757 --> 00:54:59.875
that's more than 1% a year,
so there's a very,

00:54:59.875 --> 00:55:01.400
very rapid change.
 

00:55:01.400 --> 00:55:06.525
Because of momentum the
population growth rate was 2.4%

00:55:06.525 --> 00:55:11.271
in 1965 even though the
birthrate is going down the

00:55:11.271 --> 00:55:15.070
population growth rate is going
up,

00:55:15.070 --> 00:55:19.760
all momentum,
and the percent of change that

00:55:19.760 --> 00:55:23.690
the growth rate increased by
19%,

00:55:23.690 --> 00:55:25.510
again all of this,
because at this age,

00:55:25.510 --> 00:55:27.030
they had been having a
population explosion,

00:55:27.030 --> 00:55:29.590
so many younger children than
older.

00:55:29.590 --> 00:55:34.230
The population almost doubled
from 12 million to 22 million,

00:55:34.230 --> 00:55:39.516
population went up 83% and the
annual population growth rate

00:55:39.516 --> 00:55:43.639
increased from a quarter million
to 600,000;

00:55:43.639 --> 00:55:48.809
0.6 million, it changed 217%.
 

00:55:48.809 --> 00:55:50.869
Here's the dilemma for
developing countries,

00:55:50.869 --> 00:55:55.094
that basically all the
developing countries understand

00:55:55.094 --> 00:55:58.492
that they need--
that economically they'll be

00:55:58.492 --> 00:56:02.277
destroyed if their population
growth rate increases and

00:56:02.277 --> 00:56:05.994
virtually every developing
country has now an official

00:56:05.994 --> 00:56:09.989
national policy of trying to get
its birthrate down.

00:56:09.989 --> 00:56:12.619
We'll see later that that's
okay with the people,

00:56:12.619 --> 00:56:15.521
they're generally in accord
with this, and they can do

00:56:15.521 --> 00:56:17.329
wonder--they can do miracles.
 

00:56:17.329 --> 00:56:19.755
These countries--you'll see
some of the drops next time,

00:56:19.755 --> 00:56:22.402
I'll talk about--next time in
my lecture I'll talk about some

00:56:22.402 --> 00:56:23.550
of the fabulous drops.
 

00:56:23.550 --> 00:56:28.126
I mean this is not exceptional,
this is a very significant drop

00:56:28.126 --> 00:56:31.449
but it's not exceptional around
the world,

00:56:31.449 --> 00:56:36.619
and yet, even in the face of
that, their population goes up

00:56:36.619 --> 00:56:40.159
into massive amounts,
83% up, 100% up,

00:56:40.159 --> 00:56:41.909
more than somewhat.
 

00:56:41.909 --> 00:56:45.150
As the government is pushing
modernization,

00:56:45.150 --> 00:56:49.380
and as the government is
pushing reducing the birthrate,

00:56:49.380 --> 00:56:53.094
and as grass roots
organizations push to try to get

00:56:53.094 --> 00:56:56.389
the birthrate down,
the population keeps increasing.

00:56:56.389 --> 00:56:59.320
Industrial development,
if it's not extremely rapid,

00:56:59.320 --> 00:57:02.257
can't keep up with the
birthrate, so while these

00:57:02.257 --> 00:57:06.320
countries are modernizing they
can see conditions deteriorate,

00:57:06.320 --> 00:57:09.010
poverty can grow,
crowding can grow,

00:57:09.010 --> 00:57:12.739
homelessness can grow,
again because population,

00:57:12.739 --> 00:57:16.010
even though you get your
birthrate down,

00:57:16.010 --> 00:57:20.809
your population keeps
increasing so extremely.

00:57:20.809 --> 00:57:25.186
Some theory--believe that
there's kind of a window of

00:57:25.186 --> 00:57:29.309
opportunity for the developing
countries that,

00:57:29.309 --> 00:57:32.480
for instance,
you take Egypt which I'm sure

00:57:32.480 --> 00:57:36.329
it's also had one of these drops
not unlike this.

00:57:36.329 --> 00:57:39.400
They were kings of the world,
top of the world in the

00:57:39.400 --> 00:57:41.760
Pharaoh's time,
you all know that kind of

00:57:41.760 --> 00:57:42.469
history.
 

00:57:42.469 --> 00:57:45.181
Then iron was invented,
but not in Egypt,

00:57:45.181 --> 00:57:49.250
and Egypt was in the bronze age
during the Pharaoh's time.

00:57:49.250 --> 00:57:52.572
Iron is invented maybe in
Turkey, I don't know exactly

00:57:52.572 --> 00:57:56.273
where and the other people's of
the world picked up iron and

00:57:56.273 --> 00:57:57.590
made iron swords.
 

00:57:57.590 --> 00:57:59.099
The Egyptians,
for some reason,

00:57:59.099 --> 00:58:01.652
never really caught onto iron,
maybe they don't have any iron

00:58:01.652 --> 00:58:04.405
anywhere there,
and so from 1000 BC or

00:58:04.405 --> 00:58:10.940
something until 1950 they were
always subject to somebody else.

00:58:10.940 --> 00:58:15.445
They were always ruled by
someone else until Nasser got

00:58:15.445 --> 00:58:19.402
rid of the British in 1950,
they were ruled by the British,

00:58:19.402 --> 00:58:21.090
and then before that by the
Turks,

00:58:21.090 --> 00:58:26.280
and by all kinds of peoples,
the Greeks before that--

00:58:26.280 --> 00:58:27.909
in Alexander the Greats time
and so forth,

00:58:27.909 --> 00:58:29.746
and the Romans,
they were ruled by someone

00:58:29.746 --> 00:58:30.059
else.
 

00:58:30.059 --> 00:58:34.061
Well here come--here's 1952 I
think, Nasser's revolution,

00:58:34.061 --> 00:58:37.420
gets rids of the British,
sets up an independent

00:58:37.420 --> 00:58:38.349
republic.
 

00:58:38.349 --> 00:58:40.394
The people are very
enthusiastic,

00:58:40.394 --> 00:58:43.918
they're very excited,
they now throw off the shackles

00:58:43.918 --> 00:58:46.088
of imperialism,
and colonialism,

00:58:46.088 --> 00:58:48.719
and they can now be their own
country.

00:58:48.719 --> 00:58:53.021
But the birthrate is still very
high, the population growth rate

00:58:53.021 --> 00:58:56.025
is very high,
they have to industrialize real

00:58:56.025 --> 00:58:56.639
fast.
 

00:58:56.639 --> 00:58:59.197
They can't and they don't
industrialize that fast,

00:58:59.197 --> 00:59:01.130
they don't modernize their
economy.

00:59:01.130 --> 00:59:01.355
Why?
 

00:59:01.355 --> 00:59:04.403
A whole lot of reasons,
one of which is they waste huge

00:59:04.403 --> 00:59:07.170
amounts of money on the conflict
with Israel,

00:59:07.170 --> 00:59:10.487
that they have war after war,
and have to spend huge amounts

00:59:10.487 --> 00:59:13.804
of money on the military that
would be better spent on their

00:59:13.804 --> 00:59:15.210
economic development.
 

00:59:15.210 --> 00:59:18.342
Time passes,
and the people have tried to

00:59:18.342 --> 00:59:20.494
modernize,
that's been the ideology,

00:59:20.494 --> 00:59:22.309
they've tried socialist
modernization,

00:59:22.309 --> 00:59:24.900
they've tried capitalist
modernization,

00:59:24.900 --> 00:59:28.440
and what they see is more and
more crowding,

00:59:28.440 --> 00:59:30.090
poverty is not going away.
 

00:59:30.090 --> 00:59:32.010
Conditions are not getting very
much better.

00:59:32.010 --> 00:59:35.880
I mean they do get a little bit
better, but not terribly much

00:59:35.880 --> 00:59:38.849
better and so they give up on
modernization.

00:59:38.849 --> 00:59:41.608
When they give up on
modernization they glorify the

00:59:41.608 --> 00:59:43.266
past,
they say it was better in the

00:59:43.266 --> 00:59:45.454
past,
and they go to a romantic

00:59:45.454 --> 00:59:48.030
attitude to what it was like
in--

00:59:48.030 --> 00:59:52.422
and can try to reverse
modernization by resisting

00:59:52.422 --> 00:59:56.273
further drops in birthrate,
for instance,

00:59:56.273 --> 00:59:58.309
going back to religion.
 

00:59:58.309 --> 01:00:00.429
When I was in Egypt some years
back,

01:00:00.429 --> 01:00:02.726
went into some sort of a
restaurant and they seat you

01:00:02.726 --> 01:00:06.106
sometime at long tables,
so people you don't know you

01:00:06.106 --> 01:00:09.079
sit next to,
and if they happen to speak

01:00:09.079 --> 01:00:12.849
English I could talk to them,
I don't speak Arabic,

01:00:12.849 --> 01:00:17.139
and so the ones that I could
talk to were upper class--

01:00:17.139 --> 01:00:20.076
educated people and therefore
upper class people that spoke

01:00:20.076 --> 01:00:21.190
fairly good English.
 

01:00:21.190 --> 01:00:24.402
And you meet this nice young
woman and she was at the

01:00:24.402 --> 01:00:27.369
University of Cairo which is an
elite school,

01:00:27.369 --> 01:00:29.989
and she was an engineering
student,

01:00:29.989 --> 01:00:32.820
so perfectly intelligent,
perfectly modern in that way,

01:00:32.820 --> 01:00:35.878
wearing a head scarf,
which her mother did not wear

01:00:35.878 --> 01:00:38.510
which was not in the previous
generation.

01:00:38.510 --> 01:00:41.768
That she doesn't believe in
modernization basically.

01:00:41.768 --> 01:00:44.291
For her own self-benefit she'll
become an engineer because she

01:00:44.291 --> 01:00:45.159
wants a decent job.
 

01:00:45.159 --> 01:00:49.639
She doesn't want to herself go
back and dig in the desert dirt

01:00:49.639 --> 01:00:51.989
there to try to get some food.
 

01:00:51.989 --> 01:00:54.206
She wants to be a modern person
with a good job,

01:00:54.206 --> 01:00:56.849
at least she wants a good job,
but she doesn't believe in

01:00:56.849 --> 01:00:57.699
modernization.
 

01:00:57.699 --> 01:01:00.681
The rest of her ideology,
aside from her personal

01:01:00.681 --> 01:01:04.347
desires, is backward looking,
that things were better in the

01:01:04.347 --> 01:01:06.768
past, modernization has not
worked.

01:01:06.768 --> 01:01:10.728
This is--there's this window of
opportunity when countries first

01:01:10.728 --> 01:01:14.688
try to get modernized and one of
the things that goes along with

01:01:14.688 --> 01:01:17.579
modernization is a reduced
fertility rate.

01:01:17.579 --> 01:01:20.679
If it doesn't work people will
reject that.

01:01:20.679 --> 01:01:24.840
A lot of what's going on in the
world today with respect to the

01:01:24.840 --> 01:01:27.659
developed and underdeveloped
countries,

01:01:27.659 --> 01:01:29.949
and the Arab countries,
and the Western countries,

01:01:29.949 --> 01:01:35.041
has to do with this rejection
of modernization because it did

01:01:35.041 --> 01:01:36.739
not work for them.
 

01:01:36.739 --> 01:01:38.880
With that, if the birthrate
stays high as it has,

01:01:38.880 --> 01:01:40.219
not in the Muslim countries.
 

01:01:40.219 --> 01:01:43.239
Many Muslim countries have had
fabulous progress,

01:01:43.239 --> 01:01:45.681
but in a lot of the Arab
countries the birthrate has

01:01:45.681 --> 01:01:48.632
stayed very high,
and there's these huge numbers

01:01:48.632 --> 01:01:52.081
of unemployed young men,
the economy cannot absorb them,

01:01:52.081 --> 01:01:56.289
they're hanging around,
they're idealistic as all young

01:01:56.289 --> 01:01:59.978
men are,
and what ideals do they pick up

01:01:59.978 --> 01:02:05.000
but going back to some imagined
past that was glorious.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:07.780
The world may hinge on this
window of opportunity.

01:02:07.780 --> 01:02:09.719
How many countries can take
advantage of it?

01:02:09.719 --> 01:02:12.409
China clearly took advantage of
it, Japan took advantage of it.

01:02:12.409 --> 01:02:14.532
A lot of the East Asian
countries took advantage of

01:02:14.532 --> 01:02:17.809
their window of opportunity,
a lot of other countries did

01:02:17.809 --> 01:02:21.380
not take advantage of their
window of opportunity.

